Note: ============================================================================
Note: Parser State
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Cursor over a pre-tokenised stream. Storing token_count up front means
every advance/peek path can range-check without a separate length scan
of the token array. Index-based cursor (rather than pointer) keeps
the parser independent of how the lexer laid out memory.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
32-byte record (4 x i64): tokens pointer (0), token_count (8), current
index (16), had_error sticky flag (24). Each token occupies 40 bytes
in the lexer's array so current_token computes tokens + current * 40.
@End Implementation

Type called "JuliaParser":
    tokens as Integer       Note: Token array
    token_count as Integer  Note: Number of tokens
    current as Integer      Note: Current token index
    had_error as Integer    Note: Error flag
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: AST Node Structure
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Hybrid AST node: fixed left/right slots support binary trees (binary
operators, dot access, type annotation) directly while the children
array handles variadic kinds (function call args, tuple elements,
array literals). This dual representation avoids allocating a child
array for every binary node, which would dominate the AST footprint.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
64-byte record (8 x i64). Offsets: node_type (0), value (8, owned
string for identifier/literal lexemes), left (16), right (24),
children pointer (32), child_count (40), line (48), column (56).
The children array is a flat pointer-array (not List) reallocated
in-place by add_child as it grows.
@End Implementation

Type called "ASTNode":
    node_type as Integer    Note: Type of AST node
    value as Integer        Note: Associated value (string, number, etc.)
    left as Integer         Note: Left child
    right as Integer        Note: Right child
    children as Integer     Note: Array of children
    child_count as Integer  Note: Number of children
    line as Integer         Note: Source line number
    column as Integer       Note: Source column number
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Parser Creation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Initialises the JuliaParser state from a pre-tokenised array. The
parser does not own the tokens — they outlive the parser since the
parse output (AST) references string lexemes held in tokens.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
32-byte allocation, OOM short-circuit to 0. Stores tokens at offset 0,
token_count at offset 8, current=0 at offset 16, had_error=0 at
offset 24. No initial token fetch — parser methods compute the
current token on demand from the array.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_parser" takes tokens as Integer, token_count as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create parser with token array

    Let parser_size be 32  Note: JuliaParser: 4 fields × 8 bytes
    Let parser be proc allocate from Layout with parser_size

    If parser is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 0, tokens
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 8, token_count
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 16, 0  Note: current = 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 24, 0  Note: had_error = 0

    Return parser
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: AST Node Management
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Factory for the uniform 64-byte ASTNode. The variant-tag-plus-shared-
fields approach lets every parser routine return a single value type
regardless of node kind, avoiding sum-type machinery in this layer.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates 64 bytes, OOM short-circuit. Writes node_type at offset 0
and zero-initialises every other slot so consumers can safely test
"is null" before accessing optional fields.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_node" takes node_type as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create new AST node

    Let node_size be 64  Note: ASTNode: 8 fields × 8 bytes
    Let node be proc allocate from Layout with node_size

    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 0, node_type
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 8, 0   Note: value
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 16, 0  Note: left
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 24, 0  Note: right
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 32, 0  Note: children
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 40, 0  Note: child_count
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 48, 0  Note: line
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 56, 0  Note: column

    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Variadic-child append for nodes that hold a children array (function
calls, arrays, tuples, blocks). The implementation grows the array
one slot at a time via realloc-copy because Julia ASTs are built
incrementally during parsing and the final arity isn't known up-front.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null-guards both parent and child. Reads existing children pointer
and child_count. If children is null, allocates an 8-byte (one slot)
array. Otherwise allocates (count+1)*8 bytes, copies the existing
slots over via a loop, deallocates the old array, and updates the
parent's children pointer. Writes the new child into slot child_count
and increments the count. The naive grow-by-one is O(n) per append
making total construction O(n^2) — acceptable for typical Julia
function arities (< 20 children) but bad for pathological inputs.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
The O(n^2) realloc-copy growth pattern is the dominant cost for
wide-arity AST nodes. A geometric-growth scheme (doubling capacity)
or moving to the canonical List type would lift this to O(n log n).
Defer until profiling proves this is the hot spot.
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "add_child" takes parent as Integer, child as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Add child node to parent

    If parent is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    If child is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parent, 32
    Let child_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parent, 40

    If children is equal to 0:
        Let new_children be proc allocate from Layout with 8
        If new_children is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parent, 32, new_children
        Set children to new_children
    Otherwise:
        Let new_size be child_count plus 1
        Let new_size_bytes be new_size multiplied by 8
        Set new_children to proc allocate from Layout with new_size_bytes

        If new_children is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If

        Let i be 0
        While i is less than child_count:
            Let child_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with children, i multiplied by 8
            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with new_children, i multiplied by 8, child_ptr
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While

        proc deallocate from Layout with children
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parent, 32, new_children
        Set children to new_children
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with children, child_count multiplied by 8, child
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parent, 40, child_count plus 1

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Token Access
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Computes the pointer to the current token by offsetting from the
tokens base. The 40-byte token stride is fixed by the lexer's record
layout — change one and the other must change in lockstep.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads tokens (offset 0), current (offset 16), token_count (offset 8).
Range-guards on current >= token_count, returning 0 (sentinel for
"past EOF"). Otherwise computes tokens + current * 40 as the token
address. The token is aliased, not copied — caller must not free it.
@End Implementation

Process called "current_token" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get current token

    Let tokens be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 0
    Let current be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 16
    Let token_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8

    If current is greater than or equal to token_count:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: The token array stores one 8-byte pointer per slot (tokenize writes
    Note: each token handle at offset index*8), so the current token is the
    Note: pointer dereferenced from slot `current`, not an inline 40-byte struct.
    Let token_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with tokens, current multiplied by 8

    Return token_ptr
End Process

@Reasoning:
Moves the cursor forward one token without checking bounds. The
caller is responsible for not advancing past EOF; current_token will
gracefully return 0 if it happens but advance does not error.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads current at offset 16, writes back current+1. Returns 1
unconditionally. No range check — over-advancement merely makes
subsequent current_token calls return 0 (EOF sentinel).
@End Implementation

Process called "advance" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Advance to next token

    Let current be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 16
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 16, current plus 1

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Predicate test of the current token's type. Used inside parser loops
to decide whether to take a branch without consuming the token.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Calls current_token; null returns 0 (no match). Otherwise reads
token_type at token offset 0 and compares. Returns 1 on match,
0 otherwise. Read-only — no cursor change.
@End Implementation

Process called "match_token" takes parser as Integer, token_type as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if current token matches type

    Let token be proc current_token with parser

    If token is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 0

    If type is equal to token_type:
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Combines match-and-advance with sticky-error on mismatch. The error
flag is set rather than message because the parser is structured to
do best-effort recovery; the caller (typically parse_block or a
specialised parser) checks had_error after the recursion returns.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Calls match_token. On match advances and returns 1. On mismatch sets
had_error at offset 24 to 1 and returns 0 without advancing — the
cursor remains on the unexpected token so the next parse_statement
or parser_block can attempt to resync.
@End Implementation

Process called "consume" takes parser as Integer, token_type as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Consume token of expected type

    Let matches be proc match_token with parser, token_type

    If matches is equal to 1:
        proc advance with parser
        Return 1
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 24, 1  Note: had_error = 1

    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Expression Parsing
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Recognizes the atomic-expression leaves of the Julia grammar: literals
(number/string/char/symbol/true/false/nothing), identifiers, macro
calls (@name), parenthesized expressions or tuples (with comma
detection), array literals (including comprehensions via array
forwarding), and quoted expressions (:expr). Anything else returns 0,
deferring error reporting to the caller's context.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads token type at the current token's offset 0. Each literal kind
creates a corresponding NODE_* node, captures the lexeme at token
offset 8 into the node's value slot, and advances. Identifiers and
symbols follow the same pattern. Macro names delegate to
parse_macro_call. Left paren advances, parses an expression, then
peeks for comma: comma triggers tuple construction by reading
remaining comma-separated expressions until the right paren; no
comma means single parenthesized expression. Left bracket delegates
to parse_array which itself decides literal-vs-comprehension. Colon
triggers a quote-expression wrapping the following expression in a
NODE_QUOTE_EXPR.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_primary" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse primary expression

    Let token be proc current_token with parser

    If token is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let token_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 0

    Note: Prefix unary operators: -x, +x, !x, ~x. The operand is the next
    Note: postfix expression so `-a.b` parses as -(a.b) and `!f(x)` as !(f(x)).
    Let is_prefix be 0
    If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_MINUS:
        Set is_prefix to 1
    End If
    If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_PLUS:
        Set is_prefix to 1
    End If
    If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_NOT:
        Set is_prefix to 1
    End If
    If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_BIT_NOT:
        Set is_prefix to 1
    End If
    If is_prefix is equal to 1:
        Let prefix_lex be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 8
        proc advance with parser
        Let prefix_operand be proc parse_postfix with parser
        Let unary be proc create_node with NODE_UNARY_OP
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with unary, 8, prefix_lex
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with unary, 24, prefix_operand
        Return unary
    End If

    Note: Literals
    If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_NUMBER:
        Let node be proc create_node with NODE_NUMBER
        Let lexeme be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 8
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 8, lexeme
        proc advance with parser
        Return node
    End If

    If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_STRING:
        Set node to proc create_node with NODE_STRING
        Set lexeme to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 8
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 8, lexeme
        proc advance with parser
        Return node
    End If

    If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_CHAR:
        Set node to proc create_node with NODE_CHAR
        Set lexeme to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 8
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 8, lexeme
        proc advance with parser
        Return node
    End If

    If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_SYMBOL:
        Set node to proc create_node with NODE_SYMBOL
        Set lexeme to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 8
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 8, lexeme
        proc advance with parser
        Return node
    End If

    If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_TRUE:
        Set node to proc create_node with NODE_TRUE
        proc advance with parser
        Return node
    End If

    If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_FALSE:
        Set node to proc create_node with NODE_FALSE
        proc advance with parser
        Return node
    End If

    If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_NOTHING:
        Set node to proc create_node with NODE_NOTHING
        proc advance with parser
        Return node
    End If

    If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER:
        Set node to proc create_node with NODE_IDENTIFIER
        Set lexeme to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 8
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 8, lexeme
        proc advance with parser
        Return node
    End If

    Note: Macro call
    If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_MACRO_NAME:
        Return proc parse_macro_call with parser
    End If

    Note: Parenthesized expression or tuple
    If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN:
        proc advance with parser
        Let expr be proc parse_expression with parser

        Note: Check for comma (tuple)
        Let next_token be proc current_token with parser
        If next_token is not equal to 0:
            Let next_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with next_token, 0

            If next_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_COMMA:
                Let tuple_node be proc create_node with NODE_TUPLE
                proc add_child with tuple_node, expr

                While next_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_COMMA:
                    proc advance with parser
                    Let elem be proc parse_expression with parser
                    proc add_child with tuple_node, elem

                    Set next_token to proc current_token with parser
                    If next_token is not equal to 0:
                        Set next_type to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with next_token, 0
                    Otherwise:
                        Set next_type to 0
                    End If
                End While

                proc consume with parser, JLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN
                Return tuple_node
            End If
        End If

        proc consume with parser, JLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN
        Return expr
    End If

    Note: Array literal
    If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_BRACKET:
        Return proc parse_array with parser
    End If

    Note: Quote expression
    If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_COLON:
        proc advance with parser
        Let quoted_expr be proc parse_expression with parser
        Set node to proc create_node with NODE_QUOTE_EXPR
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 24, quoted_expr
        Return node
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Handles all five Julia postfix operators that wrap a primary expression:
function call (...), parametric type {...}, indexing [...], field/
broadcast access ., and transpose ('). Loop accumulates postfix
operations left-to-right because Julia chains like `a(b)[c].d` parse
as ((a(b))[c]).d.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Starts with parse_primary; returns 0 if that fails. Then loops
examining the current token's type. Each iteration dispatches:
left-paren -> parse_call, left-brace -> parse_parametric_type,
left-bracket -> parse_index, dot -> parse_dot_access, transpose/
dot_transpose -> wrap current expr in a NODE_UNARY_OP with the
operator token stored in the value slot and the operand in the right
slot. Anything else exits the loop and returns the accumulated expr.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_postfix" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse postfix expressions (calls, indexing, access)

    Let expr be proc parse_primary with parser

    If expr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let token be proc current_token with parser

        If token is equal to 0:
            Return expr
        End If

        Let token_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 0

        Note: Function call or parametric type
        If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN:
            Set expr to proc parse_call with parser, expr
        Otherwise:
            If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_BRACE:
                Set expr to proc parse_parametric_type with parser, expr
            Otherwise:
                If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_BRACKET:
                    Set expr to proc parse_index with parser, expr
                Otherwise:
                    If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_DOT:
                        Set expr to proc parse_dot_access with parser, expr
                    Otherwise:
                        If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_TRANSPOSE:
                            Let trans_lex be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 8
                            Let trans_node be proc create_node with NODE_UNARY_OP
                            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with trans_node, 24, expr
                            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with trans_node, 8, trans_lex
                            proc advance with parser
                            Set expr to trans_node
                        Otherwise:
                            If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_DOT_TRANSPOSE:
                                Let dtrans_lex be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 8
                                Set trans_node to proc create_node with NODE_UNARY_OP
                                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with trans_node, 24, expr
                                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with trans_node, 8, dtrans_lex
                                proc advance with parser
                                Set expr to trans_node
                            Otherwise:
                                Return expr
                            End If
                        End If
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Return expr
End Process

@Reasoning:
Wraps a callee expression in a NODE_CALL with comma-separated arguments.
The callee comes from parse_postfix's accumulation (the expression
before the open paren). Empty argument lists are handled by checking
for immediate right-paren after the opening paren.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes the left paren. Creates a NODE_CALL with callee stored at
the left slot. If the next token isn't a right paren, parses the
first argument and loops collecting comma-separated argument
expressions. Consumes the closing right paren. Returns the assembled
call node.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_call" takes parser as Integer, callee as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse function call

    proc consume with parser, JLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN

    Let node be proc create_node with NODE_CALL
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 16, callee

    Let token be proc current_token with parser
    If token is not equal to 0:
        Let token_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 0

        If token_type is not equal to JLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN:
            Let arg be proc parse_expression with parser
            proc add_child with node, arg

            Set token to proc current_token with parser
            While token is not equal to 0:
                Set token_type to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 0

                If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_COMMA:
                    proc advance with parser
                    Set arg to proc parse_expression with parser
                    proc add_child with node, arg
                    Set token to proc current_token with parser
                Otherwise:
                    Set token to 0
                End If
            End While
        End If
    End If

    proc consume with parser, JLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN

    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Julia parametric types like `Array{Float64, 2}` or `Dict{String, Vector{Int}}`
attach type parameters to a base type using braces. The base type can
itself be a complex expression (typically an identifier or dot-access)
arrived at via parse_postfix accumulation.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes the left brace. Creates a NODE_PARAMETRIC_TYPE with base_type
stored at the left slot. Parses the first parameter expression and
loops collecting comma-separated parameter expressions. Consumes the
right brace. Each parameter is a full expression so parse_expression
handles nested parametric types and where-clauses.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_parametric_type" takes parser as Integer, base_type as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse parametric type (e.g., Array{T,N})

    proc consume with parser, JLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_BRACE

    Let node be proc create_node with NODE_PARAMETRIC_TYPE
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 16, base_type

    Let param be proc parse_expression with parser
    proc add_child with node, param

    Let token be proc current_token with parser
    While token is not equal to 0:
        Let token_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 0

        If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_COMMA:
            proc advance with parser
            Set param to proc parse_expression with parser
            proc add_child with node, param
            Set token to proc current_token with parser
        Otherwise:
            Set token to 0
        End If
    End While

    proc consume with parser, JLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_BRACE

    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Julia indexing `A[i, j]` supports multi-dimensional indexing through
comma-separated index expressions. Each dimension's index is a full
expression, allowing range expressions like `A[1:5, end]` or compound
expressions.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes left bracket. Creates a NODE_INDEX with array stored at the
left slot. Parses first index expression and loops collecting comma-
separated indices via add_child. Consumes the closing right bracket.
The `end` keyword for "last valid index" is handled by parse_expression
(treated as identifier) since Julia's `end` is context-sensitive.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_index" takes parser as Integer, array as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse array indexing

    proc consume with parser, JLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_BRACKET

    Let node be proc create_node with NODE_INDEX
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 16, array

    Let index be proc parse_expression with parser
    proc add_child with node, index

    Let token be proc current_token with parser
    While token is not equal to 0:
        Let token_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 0

        If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_COMMA:
            proc advance with parser
            Set index to proc parse_expression with parser
            proc add_child with node, index
            Set token to proc current_token with parser
        Otherwise:
            Set token to 0
        End If
    End While

    proc consume with parser, JLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_BRACKET

    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
The dot operator in Julia serves dual roles: field access (obj.field)
and broadcasting (.+, .*, etc., though those are scanned as single
tokens by the lexer). This routine handles field access where the
token following the dot is an identifier.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes the dot token. Peeks the next token; if it's an identifier,
creates a NODE_DOT_ACCESS with object at the left slot, and a
NODE_IDENTIFIER (with the identifier's lexeme) at the right slot.
Advances past the identifier and returns. If the post-dot token is
not an identifier (broadcast operator handled elsewhere via lexer
tokenization of .+ etc.), returns the unmodified object — caller
will see the dot as something other than field access.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_dot_access" takes parser as Integer, object as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse dot access (field or broadcast)

    proc consume with parser, JLexer.TOKEN_DOT

    Let token be proc current_token with parser
    Let token_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 0

    Note: Check if broadcast operation (.+, .*, etc.)
    If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER:
        Let node be proc create_node with NODE_DOT_ACCESS
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 16, object

        Let field be proc create_node with NODE_IDENTIFIER
        Let lexeme be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 8
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with field, 8, lexeme
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 24, field

        proc advance with parser
        Return node
    End If

    Return object
End Process

@Reasoning:
Julia array literals `[a, b, c]` and comprehensions `[expr for x in xs]`
share the same opening bracket. Distinguishing them requires speculative
parse: read the first expression, then check the next token. `for`
indicates a comprehension; comma or close-bracket indicates a literal.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes left bracket. Creates a NODE_ARRAY. If the next token isn't
right-bracket, parses the first element expression. Then peeks for
a TOKEN_FOR — if present, delegates immediately to parse_comprehension
with the first expression as the template. Otherwise treats the first
expression as the first array element, adds it as a child, and loops
collecting comma-separated additional elements. Consumes the closing
right bracket and returns the array node.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_array" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse array literal or comprehension

    proc consume with parser, JLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_BRACKET

    Let node be proc create_node with NODE_ARRAY

    Let token be proc current_token with parser
    If token is not equal to 0:
        Let token_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 0

        If token_type is not equal to JLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_BRACKET:
            Let first_elem be proc parse_expression with parser

            Note: Check for comprehension (for keyword after expression)
            Set token to proc current_token with parser
            If token is not equal to 0:
                Set token_type to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 0

                If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_FOR:
                    Return proc parse_comprehension with parser, first_elem
                End If
            End If

            proc add_child with node, first_elem

            Set token to proc current_token with parser
            While token is not equal to 0:
                Set token_type to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 0

                If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_COMMA:
                    proc advance with parser
                    Let elem be proc parse_expression with parser
                    proc add_child with node, elem
                    Set token to proc current_token with parser
                Otherwise:
                    Set token to 0
                End If
            End While
        End If
    End If

    proc consume with parser, JLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_BRACKET

    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Array comprehension `[expr for var in iter]` is a generator wrapped in
list collection. This implementation handles the single-generator form
only; nested generators with multiple `for` clauses and filter clauses
would need extension here.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Creates a NODE_COMPREHENSION and adds the template expression as the
first child. Consumes `for`, parses the loop variable expression,
consumes `in`, parses the iterator expression, adds both as children.
Consumes the closing right bracket. The three children are (template,
variable, iterator) in that order.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_comprehension" takes parser as Integer, expr as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse array comprehension `[template for v in iter (, v2 in iter2)* (if filter)?]`

    Let node be proc create_node with NODE_COMPREHENSION
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 16, expr

    proc consume with parser, JLexer.TOKEN_FOR

    Let var be proc parse_expression with parser
    proc consume with parser, JLexer.TOKEN_IN
    Let iter be proc parse_expression with parser

    Let gen be proc create_node with NODE_GENERATOR
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with gen, 16, var
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with gen, 24, iter
    proc add_child with node, gen

    Note: Additional comma-separated generator clauses.
    Let token be proc current_token with parser
    While token is not equal to 0:
        Let token_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 0
        If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_COMMA:
            proc advance with parser
            Let var2 be proc parse_expression with parser
            proc consume with parser, JLexer.TOKEN_IN
            Let iter2 be proc parse_expression with parser
            Let gen2 be proc create_node with NODE_GENERATOR
            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with gen2, 16, var2
            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with gen2, 24, iter2
            proc add_child with node, gen2
            Set token to proc current_token with parser
        Otherwise:
            Set token to 0
        End If
    End While

    Note: Optional filter clause `if condition`. Stored in the right slot so
    Note: the lowering can distinguish it from the generator children.
    Let filter_token be proc current_token with parser
    If filter_token is not equal to 0:
        Let filter_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with filter_token, 0
        If filter_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_IF:
            proc advance with parser
            Let filter_expr be proc parse_expression with parser
            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 24, filter_expr
        End If
    End If

    proc consume with parser, JLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_BRACKET

    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Julia macro calls like `@assert x > 0`, `@show var`, or
`@printf("%d", n)` consume arguments until end-of-line or semicolon.
Macros don't use parentheses for arg lists (though they may); this
parser handles the bare-arg form by reading until line terminators.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Creates a NODE_MACRO_CALL and captures the macro lexeme (the
`@name` token's text) into the value slot, then advances. Loops
peeking the next token; on TOKEN_NEWLINE/TOKEN_SEMICOLON/TOKEN_EOF
breaks out (by setting arg_type to TOKEN_NEWLINE — the loop guard).
Otherwise parses an expression and adds it as a child. The
arg-token re-peek after parsing prevents infinite loop on
malformed input where the macro args span more than the parser
expects.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_macro_call" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse macro call (@macro_name args)

    Let token be proc current_token with parser
    Let node be proc create_node with NODE_MACRO_CALL

    Let lexeme be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 8
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 8, lexeme

    proc advance with parser

    Note: Parse macro arguments (varies by macro)
    Let arg_token be proc current_token with parser
    If arg_token is not equal to 0:
        Let arg_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with arg_token, 0

        Note: Parse arguments until newline or semicolon
        While arg_type is not equal to JLexer.TOKEN_NEWLINE:
            If arg_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_SEMICOLON:
                Set arg_type to JLexer.TOKEN_NEWLINE
            Otherwise:
                If arg_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_EOF:
                    Set arg_type to JLexer.TOKEN_NEWLINE
                Otherwise:
                    Let arg be proc parse_expression with parser
                    proc add_child with node, arg

                    Set arg_token to proc current_token with parser
                    If arg_token is not equal to 0:
                        Set arg_type to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with arg_token, 0
                    Otherwise:
                        Set arg_type to JLexer.TOKEN_EOF
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End While
    End If

    Return node
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Binary Operators
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Returns the precedence level of a binary operator token, matching
Julia's operator precedence table. Higher numbers bind tighter. The
13-level scale runs from assignment (1, weakest) through exponentiation
(13, strongest), with the same level used for operators of equal
precedence. Zero means "not a binary operator", used by parse_binary
to detect when to stop accumulating.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Linear If-chain dispatching token_type to precedence number. Levels:
1 assignment, 2 pipe operators (|>, <|), 3 ternary ?, 4 logical OR,
5 logical AND, 6 comparisons (<, <=, >, >=, ==, !=, ===), 7 bitwise
OR, 8 bitwise XOR, 9 bitwise AND, 10 shifts (<<, >>, >>>), 11
addition/subtraction (and broadcasting .+/.-), 12 multiplication/
division/modulo (and broadcasting .*/./), 13 exponentiation (^, .^).
Unrecognised tokens return 0.
@End Implementation

Process called "get_precedence" takes token_type as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get operator precedence

    Note: Assignment (lowest)
    If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_ASSIGN:
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Arrow lambda `->` and Pair `=>` sit just above assignment so the
    Note: whole right-hand side of `x -> expr` / `k => v` is captured.
    If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_ARROW:
        Return 1
    End If
    If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_PAIR_ARROW:
        Return 2
    End If

    Note: Pipe operators
    If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_PIPE_RIGHT:
        Return 2
    End If
    If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_PIPE_LEFT:
        Return 2
    End If

    Note: Ternary (handled separately)
    If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_QUESTION:
        Return 3
    End If

    Note: Logical OR
    If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_OR:
        Return 4
    End If

    Note: Logical AND
    If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_AND:
        Return 5
    End If

    Note: Comparison
    If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_LESS:
        Return 6
    End If
    If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_LESS_EQUAL:
        Return 6
    End If
    If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_GREATER:
        Return 6
    End If
    If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_GREATER_EQUAL:
        Return 6
    End If
    If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_EQUAL:
        Return 6
    End If
    If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_NOT_EQUAL:
        Return 6
    End If
    If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_TRIPLE_EQUAL:
        Return 6
    End If

    Note: Bitwise OR
    If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_BIT_OR:
        Return 7
    End If

    Note: Bitwise XOR
    If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_BIT_XOR:
        Return 8
    End If

    Note: Bitwise AND
    If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_BIT_AND:
        Return 9
    End If

    Note: Shift operators
    If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_SHIFT:
        Return 10
    End If
    If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_SHIFT:
        Return 10
    End If
    If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_UNSIGNED_RIGHT_SHIFT:
        Return 10
    End If

    Note: Addition/Subtraction
    If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_PLUS:
        Return 11
    End If
    If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_MINUS:
        Return 11
    End If

    Note: Multiplication/Division
    If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_STAR:
        Return 12
    End If
    If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_SLASH:
        Return 12
    End If
    If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_BACKSLASH:
        Return 12
    End If
    If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_PERCENT:
        Return 12
    End If
    If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_DOUBLE_SLASH:
        Return 12
    End If

    Note: Broadcasting operators
    If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_DOT_PLUS:
        Return 11
    End If
    If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_DOT_MINUS:
        Return 11
    End If
    If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_DOT_STAR:
        Return 12
    End If
    If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_DOT_SLASH:
        Return 12
    End If
    If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_DOT_BACKSLASH:
        Return 12
    End If

    Note: Exponentiation (highest)
    If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_CARET:
        Return 13
    End If
    If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_DOT_CARET:
        Return 13
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Standard precedence-climbing recursive-descent for binary operators.
Each recursive call only consumes operators at or above min_prec,
ensuring left-association at the same precedence level and correct
nesting for mixed-precedence chains. Ternary is treated as a special
binary form (?: needs three operands).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Starts with parse_postfix for the left operand. Loops examining the
current token's precedence. Exits if precedence is 0 (non-operator)
or less than min_prec. For TOKEN_QUESTION (ternary), advances, parses
the true-branch expression, expects colon, parses the false-branch
expression, wraps in NODE_TERNARY with three children. For regular
binary operators, advances past the operator, recursively calls
parse_binary with min_prec = prec+1 (forcing left-association for
same-precedence operators), then wraps in NODE_BINARY_OP storing
operator at value slot, left and right at the binary slots.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_binary" takes parser as Integer, min_prec as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse binary expression with precedence climbing

    Let left be proc parse_postfix with parser

    If left is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let token be proc current_token with parser

        If token is equal to 0:
            Return left
        End If

        Let token_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 0
        Let prec be proc get_precedence with token_type

        If prec is equal to 0:
            Return left
        End If

        If prec is less than min_prec:
            Return left
        End If

        Note: Handle ternary specially
        If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_QUESTION:
            proc advance with parser
            Let true_expr be proc parse_expression with parser
            proc consume with parser, JLexer.TOKEN_COLON
            Let false_expr be proc parse_expression with parser

            Let ternary be proc create_node with NODE_TERNARY
            proc add_child with ternary, left
            proc add_child with ternary, true_expr
            proc add_child with ternary, false_expr

            Set left to ternary
        Otherwise:
            If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_ARROW:
                Note: Anonymous function `params -> body`. The left operand is
                Note: the parameter spec (identifier or parenthesised tuple);
                Note: the body is the right-associatively parsed remainder.
                proc advance with parser
                Let lambda_body be proc parse_binary with parser, prec
                Let lambda be proc create_node with NODE_LAMBDA
                proc add_child with lambda, left
                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lambda, 24, lambda_body
                Set left to lambda
            Otherwise:
                If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_PAIR_ARROW:
                    Note: Pair `key => value`.
                    proc advance with parser
                    Let pair_value be proc parse_binary with parser, prec plus 1
                    Let pair_node be proc create_node with NODE_PAIR
                    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with pair_node, 16, left
                    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with pair_node, 24, pair_value
                    Set left to pair_node
                Otherwise:
                    Note: Capture the operator's source lexeme (token offset 8)
                    Note: so the binary node carries a real operator string for
                    Note: the model-3 HIR contract rather than a token-type int.
                    Let op_lexeme be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 8
                    proc advance with parser

                    Let next_min be prec plus 1

                    Let right be proc parse_binary with parser, next_min

                    If right is equal to 0:
                        Return left
                    End If

                    Let node be proc create_node with NODE_BINARY_OP
                    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 8, op_lexeme
                    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 16, left
                    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 24, right

                    Set left to node
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Return left
End Process

@Reasoning:
Public expression entry point. Starts the precedence-climbing parse
with min_prec=0 so all operators are eligible. This makes
parse_expression the single recursive cycle entry for nested
expressions appearing in statements, function args, array elements,
etc.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Single-line wrapper calling parse_binary with parser and min_prec=0.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_expression" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse complete expression

    Return proc parse_binary with parser, 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Statement Parsing
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Statement dispatcher. Julia has six block-starting keywords (function,
if, for, while, return, plus break/continue), each with dedicated
parser. Anything else is treated as an expression statement —
including assignment, which is parsed as a low-precedence binary
operator (assignment is operator precedence 1).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads current token type at offset 0 and dispatches: TOKEN_FUNCTION ->
parse_function_def, TOKEN_IF -> parse_if, TOKEN_FOR -> parse_for,
TOKEN_WHILE -> parse_while, TOKEN_RETURN -> parse_return,
TOKEN_BREAK -> create NODE_BREAK_STMT and advance,
TOKEN_CONTINUE -> create NODE_CONTINUE_STMT and advance.
Anything else falls through to parse_expression, returning the
result directly as the statement.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_statement" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse statement

    Let token be proc current_token with parser

    If token is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let token_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 0

    If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_FUNCTION:
        Return proc parse_function_def with parser
    End If

    If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_IF:
        Return proc parse_if with parser
    End If

    If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_FOR:
        Return proc parse_for with parser
    End If

    If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_WHILE:
        Return proc parse_while with parser
    End If

    If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_RETURN:
        Return proc parse_return with parser
    End If

    If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_BREAK:
        proc advance with parser
        Return proc create_node with NODE_BREAK_STMT
    End If

    If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_CONTINUE:
        proc advance with parser
        Return proc create_node with NODE_CONTINUE_STMT
    End If

    If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_STRUCT:
        Return proc parse_struct_def with parser, 0
    End If

    If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_MUTABLE:
        proc advance with parser
        Return proc parse_struct_def with parser, 1
    End If

    If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_ABSTRACT:
        Return proc parse_abstract_type with parser
    End If

    If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_PRIMITIVE:
        Return proc parse_primitive_type with parser
    End If

    If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_MODULE:
        Return proc parse_module_def with parser
    End If

    If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_BAREMODULE:
        Return proc parse_module_def with parser
    End If

    If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_MACRO:
        Return proc parse_macro_def with parser
    End If

    If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_USING:
        Return proc parse_using_import with parser, NODE_USING_STMT
    End If

    If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_IMPORT:
        Return proc parse_using_import with parser, NODE_IMPORT_STMT
    End If

    If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_EXPORT:
        Return proc parse_export with parser
    End If

    If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_PUBLIC:
        Return proc parse_export with parser
    End If

    If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_CONST:
        Return proc parse_scoped_decl with parser, NODE_CONST_DECL, JLexer.TOKEN_CONST
    End If

    If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_GLOBAL:
        Return proc parse_scoped_decl with parser, NODE_GLOBAL_DECL, JLexer.TOKEN_GLOBAL
    End If

    If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_LOCAL:
        Return proc parse_scoped_decl with parser, NODE_LOCAL_DECL, JLexer.TOKEN_LOCAL
    End If

    If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_LET:
        Return proc parse_let_block with parser
    End If

    If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_BEGIN:
        Return proc parse_begin_block with parser
    End If

    If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_TRY:
        Return proc parse_try with parser
    End If

    If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_QUOTE:
        Return proc parse_quote_block with parser
    End If

    If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_MACRO_NAME:
        Return proc parse_macro_call with parser
    End If

    Note: Expression statement (including assignment)
    Let expr be proc parse_expression with parser

    Note:
    Julia short-form function definition: `name(params...) = body`. The
    expression parser lowers this to a NODE_BINARY_OP whose operator is
    TOKEN_ASSIGN and whose left operand is a NODE_CALL. That is exactly a
    function definition, so rewrite it into the same NODE_FUNCTION_DEF shape
    the long `function ... end` form produces: function name in the value
    slot, parameters as children, body in the right slot. This keeps the two
    definition forms structurally identical for every downstream consumer.
    :End Note
    If expr is equal to 0:
        Return expr
    End If

    Let expr_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with expr, 0
    If expr_type is equal to NODE_BINARY_OP:
        Note: The operator slot now holds the source lexeme string (set by
        Note: parse_binary), so detect assignment by comparing against "=".
        Let op be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with expr, 8
        Let op_is_assign be proc string_equals from StringCore with op, "="
        If op_is_assign is equal to 1:
            Let lhs be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with expr, 16
            Let lhs_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lhs, 0
            If lhs_type is equal to NODE_CALL:
                Let func_node be proc create_node with NODE_FUNCTION_DEF

                Note: Function name: the call's callee (offset 16). When the
                Note: callee is a bare identifier its name handle lives in the
                Note: callee's value slot; copy it into the function node.
                Let callee be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lhs, 16
                If callee is not equal to 0:
                    Let callee_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with callee, 0
                    If callee_type is equal to NODE_IDENTIFIER:
                        Let fname be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with callee, 8
                        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with func_node, 8, fname
                    End If
                End If

                Note: Parameters: the call's argument children become the
                Note: function's parameter children, preserving order.
                Let arg_children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lhs, 32
                Let arg_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lhs, 40
                Let pi be 0
                While pi is less than arg_count:
                    Let arg be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with arg_children, pi multiplied by 8
                    proc add_child with func_node, arg
                    Set pi to pi plus 1
                End While

                Note: Body: the assignment's right operand becomes the body.
                Let body be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with expr, 24
                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with func_node, 24, body

                Return func_node
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Return expr
End Process

@Reasoning:
Julia function definition: `function name(p1::T1, p2::T2)::RetType body
end`. All parts after the name are optional in different ways:
parameters may be empty, type annotations on parameters and return
type are optional. The body uses block syntax terminated by `end`.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes `function`. Creates a NODE_FUNCTION_DEF. Captures function
name from the next identifier into value slot. Consumes opening
paren. The parameter loop reads first param via parse_parameter,
then loops on comma-separated parameters. Consumes closing paren.
Then checks for `::` (TOKEN_DOUBLE_COLON) indicating return type
annotation — if present, advances and parses the type expression
into the left slot. Then parses the body via parse_block with
TOKEN_END as the terminator, stores body in right slot. Finally
consumes `end`.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_function_def" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse function definition

    proc consume with parser, JLexer.TOKEN_FUNCTION

    Let node be proc create_node with NODE_FUNCTION_DEF

    Note: Function name
    Let name_token be proc current_token with parser
    Let name_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with name_token, 0

    If name_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER:
        Let name be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with name_token, 8
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 8, name
        proc advance with parser
    End If

    Note: Parameters
    proc consume with parser, JLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN

    Let param_token be proc current_token with parser
    If param_token is not equal to 0:
        Let param_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with param_token, 0

        If param_type is not equal to JLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN:
            Let param be proc parse_parameter with parser
            proc add_child with node, param

            Set param_token to proc current_token with parser
            While param_token is not equal to 0:
                Set param_type to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with param_token, 0

                If param_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_COMMA:
                    proc advance with parser
                    Set param to proc parse_parameter with parser
                    proc add_child with node, param
                    Set param_token to proc current_token with parser
                Otherwise:
                    Set param_token to 0
                End If
            End While
        End If
    End If

    proc consume with parser, JLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN

    Note: Return type annotation
    Let ret_token be proc current_token with parser
    If ret_token is not equal to 0:
        Let ret_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ret_token, 0

        If ret_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_DOUBLE_COLON:
            proc advance with parser
            Let type_expr be proc parse_expression with parser
            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 16, type_expr
        End If
    End If

    Note: Body
    Let body be proc parse_block with parser, JLexer.TOKEN_END

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 24, body

    proc consume with parser, JLexer.TOKEN_END

    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Single function parameter: either `name` (no type) or `name::Type`
(with type annotation). The annotated case produces a
NODE_TYPE_ANNOTATION wrapper so downstream multiple-dispatch analysis
can inspect the type without re-parsing the AST.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads the parameter name identifier — bails out returning 0 if not
an identifier (caller will see the failure as had_error if it
mattered). Creates a NODE_IDENTIFIER with the name lexeme.
Peeks the next token for `::`. If present, advances, parses the
type expression, then wraps both in a NODE_TYPE_ANNOTATION with
identifier in left slot and type in right slot, returning the
wrapper. Otherwise returns the bare identifier node.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_parameter" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse function parameter

    Let param_token be proc current_token with parser
    Let param_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with param_token, 0

    If param_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER:
        Let param_node be proc create_node with NODE_IDENTIFIER
        Let name be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with param_token, 8
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with param_node, 8, name
        proc advance with parser

        Let result be param_node

        Note: Type annotation
        Let next_token be proc current_token with parser
        If next_token is not equal to 0:
            Let next_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with next_token, 0

            If next_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_DOUBLE_COLON:
                proc advance with parser
                Let type_expr be proc parse_expression with parser

                Let annotated be proc create_node with NODE_TYPE_ANNOTATION
                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with annotated, 16, param_node
                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with annotated, 24, type_expr

                Set result to annotated
            End If
        End If

        Note: Default / keyword value: `name = expr` or `name::Type = expr`.
        Note: Modelled as a NODE_BINARY_OP with the "=" lexeme so the value
        Note: round-trips through binary_op without a dedicated node kind.
        Let dflt_token be proc current_token with parser
        If dflt_token is not equal to 0:
            Let dflt_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with dflt_token, 0
            If dflt_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_ASSIGN:
                Let dflt_lex be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with dflt_token, 8
                proc advance with parser
                Let dflt_value be proc parse_expression with parser
                Let dflt_node be proc create_node with NODE_BINARY_OP
                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with dflt_node, 8, dflt_lex
                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with dflt_node, 16, result
                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with dflt_node, 24, dflt_value
                Set result to dflt_node
            End If
        End If

        Return result
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Julia if has the form: if cond block [elseif cond block]* [else block]
end. Children alternate condition/block in declaration order so a
downstream consumer can iterate pairs.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes `if`. Creates a NODE_IF_STMT. Parses condition and adds as
child, parses then-block (parse_block with TOKEN_END as terminator)
and adds as child. Then loops examining elseif/else: TOKEN_ELSEIF
advances, parses next condition + block (both added as children).
TOKEN_ELSE advances, parses else block (only the block as child).
Anything else exits the loop. Consumes the closing `end`.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_if" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse if statement

    proc consume with parser, JLexer.TOKEN_IF

    Let node be proc create_node with NODE_IF_STMT

    Let cond be proc parse_expression with parser
    proc add_child with node, cond

    Let then_block be proc parse_block_until with parser

    proc add_child with node, then_block

    Note: Check for elseif/else
    Let next_token be proc current_token with parser
    While next_token is not equal to 0:
        Let next_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with next_token, 0

        If next_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_ELSEIF:
            proc advance with parser
            Let elseif_cond be proc parse_expression with parser
            proc add_child with node, elseif_cond

            Let elseif_block be proc parse_block_until with parser
            proc add_child with node, elseif_block

            Set next_token to proc current_token with parser
        Otherwise:
            If next_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_ELSE:
                proc advance with parser
                Let else_block be proc parse_block_until with parser
                proc add_child with node, else_block
                Set next_token to 0
            Otherwise:
                Set next_token to 0
            End If
        End If
    End While

    proc consume with parser, JLexer.TOKEN_END

    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Julia for-loop: `for var in iterable body end`. Both var and iterable
are full expressions (var supports tuple destructuring patterns).
Three children: variable, iterator, body — in order.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes `for`. Creates NODE_FOR_STMT. Parses loop variable
expression, consumes `in`, parses iterator expression, adds both
as children. Parses body via parse_block with TOKEN_END, adds as
child. Consumes closing `end`.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_for" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse for loop

    proc consume with parser, JLexer.TOKEN_FOR

    Let node be proc create_node with NODE_FOR_STMT

    Let var be proc parse_expression with parser
    proc consume with parser, JLexer.TOKEN_IN
    Let iter be proc parse_expression with parser

    proc add_child with node, var
    proc add_child with node, iter

    Let body be proc parse_block with parser, JLexer.TOKEN_END

    proc add_child with node, body

    proc consume with parser, JLexer.TOKEN_END

    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Julia while-loop: `while cond body end`. Two children: condition then
body.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes `while`. Creates NODE_WHILE_STMT. Parses condition and adds
as child. Parses body via parse_block with TOKEN_END, adds as child.
Consumes closing `end`.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_while" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse while loop

    proc consume with parser, JLexer.TOKEN_WHILE

    Let node be proc create_node with NODE_WHILE_STMT

    Let cond be proc parse_expression with parser
    proc add_child with node, cond

    Let body be proc parse_block with parser, JLexer.TOKEN_END

    proc add_child with node, body

    proc consume with parser, JLexer.TOKEN_END

    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Julia `return` can be valueless (returns nothing) or take an
expression. Distinguishing the two requires peeking: if the next
token is a statement terminator (newline/semicolon) or `end`, no
expression follows; otherwise parse one.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes `return`. Creates NODE_RETURN_STMT. Peeks current token —
if it's not TOKEN_NEWLINE, TOKEN_SEMICOLON, or TOKEN_END, parses
an expression and stores it at offset 24 (the right slot). Otherwise
returns the bare return node with no value slot. Used by
parse_statement on TOKEN_RETURN dispatch.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_return" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse return statement

    proc consume with parser, JLexer.TOKEN_RETURN

    Let node be proc create_node with NODE_RETURN_STMT

    Let token be proc current_token with parser
    If token is not equal to 0:
        Let token_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 0

        If token_type is not equal to JLexer.TOKEN_NEWLINE:
            If token_type is not equal to JLexer.TOKEN_SEMICOLON:
                If token_type is not equal to JLexer.TOKEN_END:
                    Let value be proc parse_expression with parser
                    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 24, value
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
General block parser that reads statements until a specific terminator
token (passed by the caller, typically TOKEN_END or TOKEN_EOF). Used
by function bodies, if-branches, loop bodies, and the top-level
parse_program. The terminator parameter lets the same routine serve
all block contexts without parser-specific branching.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Creates a NODE_PROGRAM (overloaded as "block of statements" — name
is historical). Loops until current token type equals end_token or
EOF. Each iteration skips newlines and semicolons silently (they
separate but don't terminate statements). Otherwise calls
parse_statement and adds the result as a child if non-null.
Returns the block on encountering the terminator (without consuming
it — that's the caller's job).
@End Implementation

@Reasoning:
Julia struct definition: `[mutable] struct Name[{T...}] [<: Super] fields...
end`. Each field is `name` or `name::Type`, parsed by parse_parameter so a
typed field becomes a NODE_TYPE_ANNOTATION. The struct name (with any
parametric/supertype expression) is stored in the value slot for a bare
identifier or in the left slot for a richer head expression. The mutable
flag is recorded in the value-type-adjacent column (offset 48, the `line`
slot is repurposed-free here) — instead we store mutability in the right
slot as a sentinel node-free flag using column offset 56. To keep the
schema clean we store the is_mutable flag at offset 48 (the otherwise
unused column slot is fine for a leaf-less struct head).
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Consumes `struct`. Reads the head expression (identifier, possibly followed
by `{params}` and `<: Super`) via parse_expression so `Point{T} <: Any`
parses fully; the head's leading identifier name is copied into the value
slot when it is a bare identifier, otherwise the whole head is kept in the
left slot. is_mutable is written to offset 48. Fields are parsed with
parse_block_until-style iteration: each non-separator line is a field via
parse_parameter, added as a child. Consumes the closing `end`.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_struct_def" takes parser as Integer, is_mutable as Integer returns Integer:
    proc consume with parser, JLexer.TOKEN_STRUCT

    Let node be proc create_node with NODE_STRUCT_DEF
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 48, is_mutable

    Note: Struct head: Name, possibly Name{T...} and/or Name <: Super.
    Let head be proc parse_expression with parser
    If head is not equal to 0:
        Let head_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with head, 0
        If head_type is equal to NODE_IDENTIFIER:
            Let hname be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with head, 8
            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 8, hname
        Otherwise:
            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 16, head
        End If
    End If

    Note: Field list until `end`.
    Let token be proc current_token with parser
    While token is not equal to 0:
        Let token_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 0
        If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_END:
            Set token to 0
        Otherwise:
            If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_EOF:
                Set token to 0
            Otherwise:
                If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_NEWLINE:
                    proc advance with parser
                    Set token to proc current_token with parser
                Otherwise:
                    If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_SEMICOLON:
                        proc advance with parser
                        Set token to proc current_token with parser
                    Otherwise:
                        Let before be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 16
                        Let field be proc parse_struct_member with parser
                        If field is not equal to 0:
                            proc add_child with node, field
                        End If
                        Let after be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 16
                        If after is equal to before:
                            Set token to 0
                        Otherwise:
                            Set token to proc current_token with parser
                        End If
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End While

    proc consume with parser, JLexer.TOKEN_END
    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
A struct member is either a typed/untyped field (`name` / `name::Type`),
an inner-constructor function definition, or a `name = default`. The field
case reuses parse_parameter (which yields a NODE_TYPE_ANNOTATION for typed
fields). A `function` start delegates to parse_function_def so inner
constructors round-trip. Anything else is parsed as a full expression so
default-valued fields survive.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_struct_member" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let token be proc current_token with parser
    If token is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let token_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 0

    If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_FUNCTION:
        Return proc parse_function_def with parser
    End If

    If token_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER:
        Return proc parse_parameter with parser
    End If

    Return proc parse_expression with parser
End Process

@Reasoning:
Julia abstract type: `abstract type Name [<: Super] end`. The head is a
full expression so `Name{T} <: Super` parses; a bare identifier name is
lifted into the value slot, the optional supertype (the right operand of
`<:`) into the left slot.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_abstract_type" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    proc consume with parser, JLexer.TOKEN_ABSTRACT
    proc consume with parser, JLexer.TOKEN_TYPE

    Let node be proc create_node with NODE_ABSTRACT_TYPE

    Let head be proc parse_expression with parser
    If head is not equal to 0:
        Let head_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with head, 0
        If head_type is equal to NODE_IDENTIFIER:
            Let hname be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with head, 8
            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 8, hname
        Otherwise:
            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 16, head
        End If
    End If

    proc consume with parser, JLexer.TOKEN_END
    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Julia primitive type: `primitive type Name [<: Super] Bits end`, where Bits
is the integer bit-width. The head (Name and optional `<: Super`) is parsed
as an expression, then the trailing bit-count expression is captured in the
left slot. A bare identifier name is lifted to the value slot.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_primitive_type" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    proc consume with parser, JLexer.TOKEN_PRIMITIVE
    proc consume with parser, JLexer.TOKEN_TYPE

    Let node be proc create_node with NODE_PRIMITIVE_TYPE

    Let head be proc parse_expression with parser
    If head is not equal to 0:
        Let head_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with head, 0
        If head_type is equal to NODE_IDENTIFIER:
            Let hname be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with head, 8
            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 8, hname
        Otherwise:
            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 24, head
        End If
    End If

    Note: The bit-width expression directly precedes `end`.
    Let token be proc current_token with parser
    If token is not equal to 0:
        Let token_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 0
        If token_type is not equal to JLexer.TOKEN_END:
            Let bits be proc parse_expression with parser
            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 16, bits
        End If
    End If

    proc consume with parser, JLexer.TOKEN_END
    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Julia module: `module Name body... end` (baremodule shares the same shape).
The module name is captured into the value slot; the body statements become
children. The body is a normal statement block terminated by `end`.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_module_def" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Consume `module` or `baremodule`.
    proc advance with parser

    Let node be proc create_node with NODE_MODULE_DEF

    Let name_token be proc current_token with parser
    If name_token is not equal to 0:
        Let name_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with name_token, 0
        If name_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER:
            Let name be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with name_token, 8
            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 8, name
            proc advance with parser
        End If
    End If

    Let body be proc parse_block with parser, JLexer.TOKEN_END
    Let bcount be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with body, 40
    Let bchildren be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with body, 32
    Let bi be 0
    While bi is less than bcount:
        Let stmt be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with bchildren, bi multiplied by 8
        proc add_child with node, stmt
        Set bi to bi plus 1
    End While

    proc consume with parser, JLexer.TOKEN_END
    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Julia macro definition: `macro name(args...) body end`. Structurally a
function definition (name in value slot, params as children, body in right
slot) with a distinct node kind so the lowering can tag it is_macro.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_macro_def" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    proc consume with parser, JLexer.TOKEN_MACRO

    Let node be proc create_node with NODE_MACRO_DEF

    Let name_token be proc current_token with parser
    If name_token is not equal to 0:
        Let name_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with name_token, 0
        If name_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER:
            Let name be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with name_token, 8
            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 8, name
            proc advance with parser
        End If
    End If

    proc consume with parser, JLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN
    Let param_token be proc current_token with parser
    If param_token is not equal to 0:
        Let param_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with param_token, 0
        If param_type is not equal to JLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN:
            Let param be proc parse_parameter with parser
            proc add_child with node, param
            Set param_token to proc current_token with parser
            While param_token is not equal to 0:
                Set param_type to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with param_token, 0
                If param_type is equal to JLexer.TOKEN_COMMA:
                    proc advance with parser
                    Set param to proc parse_parameter with parser
                    proc add_child with node, param
                    Set param_token to proc current_token with parser
                Otherwise:
                    Set param_token to 0
                End If
            End While
        End If
    End If
    proc consume with parser, JLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN

    Let body be proc parse_block with parser, JLexer.TOKEN_END
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 24, body
    proc consume with parser, JLexer.TOKEN_END
    Return node
